# White Paper

The White Paper serves as the principal conceptual reference for EGL.

Its primary objectives are to:

- define the governance problem of premature institutional closure;
- establish the public-law foundations of EGL;
- introduce the Composite Public Law Control Matrix;
- explain pathway governance and closure gates;
- describe institutional evidence and review-ready governance;
- provide a foundation for future academic research and institutional implementation.

The White Paper is intended primarily for:

- researchers;
- legal scholars;
- policymakers;
- regulators;
- institutional leaders;
- governance professionals.

---

# Specification Library

The Specification Library provides the normative implementation documents for EGL.

Each specification defines a particular component of the framework, including:

- terminology;
- required controls;
- governance rules;
- evidence requirements;
- pathway logic;
- maturity criteria;
- implementation expectations.

Specifications are designed to support:

- institutional implementation;
- software integration;
- procurement requirements;
- governance reviews;
- audit and assurance activities;
- future technical development.

---

# Relationship Between the Two

The White Paper answers:

> **Why should AI-assisted institutional pathways remain open before consequential closure?**

The Specifications answer:

> **How should institutions operationalize that principle through structured governance controls, pathway management, evidence, and review mechanisms?**

The two components are complementary.

The White Paper establishes the conceptual and doctrinal foundations.

The Specification Library provides the operational architecture.

Together they constitute the official public specification of the Elastic Governance Layer (EGL).

